answers. His first destination is Takish-Hiz.<br>
<br>
Backstory still in progress, but esentially Marrik is a wandering philosopher trying to answer the age old questions of why are we here and what does it all mean. I have yet to run into someone who seemed interested in debating theology (Heck, I have yet to really find someone to talk period) in game, so I thought I would post some of my first thoughts here. These are mostly rhetorical, meant to inspire comments, not real answers.  <br>
<br>
 --<br>
 Excerpt from Marrik's personal journal:<br>
 --<br>
It occured to me today that the Teir'dal and Koada'dal are RACIAL enemies, not IDEOLOGICAL or RELIGOUS enemies.  <br>
<br>
To be simplistic, Tier'dal are evil (I don't necessarily believe this, but I think most of my peers would agree with this statement without thought), they worship the god of hate. The opposite of hate is love, Erollisi Marr. The other 'evil' gods are Bertoxxulous, his opposite is Rodcet Nife. Cazic-Thule, his opposite is Mithaniel Marr. I don't know<br>
if Rallos Zek is 'evil', but even so his opposite is<br>
Quellious. [Penciled in the margin, &quot; Who is opposite the wheel from Tunare? Solusek? Perhaps nothing, Perhaps Tunare and Karana exist in the hub&quot;]<br>
<br>
Point being that Tunare is not against the evil gods. The only reason she became involved in our time is due to imbalance pushed on the world by Innoruuk and the current existance of Malevolence. Had Erollisi Marr created an 'Avatar of Love' and handed her the  &quot;LoveBringer&quot; (made<br>
that up) to bring death and destruction to Neriak and Ogguk, would not the fair Tunare jump in on the side of evil? [penciled in the margin, &quot;maybe not, consider the balance of order and chaos as well&quot;] <br>
<br>
Which makes you wonder why the Marr twins are not at the forefront of the recent events. <br>
<br>
Tunare is about nature and balance. What is the rule of the jungle but the strong live and the weak perish. This seems at odds with the 'good' nature of high elves and more in tune with our dark skinned brethren. There is nothing 'evil' about the wolf killing a lamb, it just is. <br>
<br>
I wonder if Tunare allowed the prince of hate to take her first born and corrupt them to evil, such that good could exist in the world. For without the existance of evil, there can be no good, or balance is lost. <br>
<br>
Ah but wait. I have not yet considered the implications of order vs. chaos. Throughout my youth I was told that Tunare and High Elves represent all that is good and orderly in the world. But yet, Tunare is the godess of Nature, and nature abhors a straight line. The jungles constantly strive to reclaim the 'order' we impose in our cities and castles. <br>
<br>
As a mere mortal, perhaps it is arrogant of me to presume I have the facilities to understand the motivations and goals of our dieties. <br>
<br>
I must think upon these matters more, it is unfortunate I cannot find anyone willing to parlay with me on these topics. <br>
<br>
--<br>
<br>
Unfortunately Marrik wondered these thoughts aloud and was subtley shunned from 'proper' society. He quietly closed down his shop and headed out into the woods to find his answers. <br>
<br>
Marrik LFG<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=jaelyndimathe>Jaelyn DiMathe</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 3<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(1/17/02 12:07:53 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1137.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: A crisis of faith (long)</span><hr size=1> I think part of the problem is your misinterpretation of the motivation of the Tier'dal, and the assumption that they and the high elves are not ideologically opposed.  To understand this, one must ponder the definition of what they stand for, and what they worship - hate.  <br>
<br>
To truly worship hate, one must by definition be constantly in disaccord with everything around them.  They despise all they come in contact with, seek to conquer or destroy that which will not bend to their will, and use whatever means necessary to accomplish this goal, be it power, money, or people.  Even the most devote follower would gladly destroy his/her god and take his place if possible.  The only thing that keeps them in-line is fear.  There can be no true respect among the denizens of hate, as respect grows from understanding and, if I'm not stepping too far, love.  If you despise all around you, you can not respect anything.  Rather, you tolerate until you can bend to your will.  As such, their society is built upon the knowledge of mutually assured destruction.  Order is imposed simply because they know that to step out of bounds is to be destroyed.  Unless, of course, you are the more powerful, in which case society's order will reflect your vision, until some more powerful yet supercedes you.  Such is the nature of hate.<br>
<br>
To this, you compare the Goddess of Love bringing about a &quot;Lovebringer&quot;, if such an object exists.  What would this item do, and what is the true goal of Love?  You seem to think it's to destroy and kill the evil races, which is a slap in the face of what love truly is.  Love seeks to guide, to show compassion, to nuture, not to destroy and maim.  A true disciple of the Goddess would seek by actions and words to show the Tier'dal the error of their ways, and the ultimate destructive nature of their &quot;God&quot;.  A lovebringer would change the hearts, not rend the flesh.  Compassion, tolerance, understanding, cooperation...these are the things that would be brought about by the kind of intervention you speak of the Goddess of Love making.<br>
<br>
Now, if that were to happen, what would Tunare's response be.  You seem to think she would take the side of evil, to correct the &quot;balance.&quot;  Again, I think you misinterpret her wishes, though I seek not to overstep my station by attempting to put words or thoughts into the mouth and mind of Tunare.  She is a goddess of balance and nature, true, but only goodness can achieve true balance.  A world touched by love would not be one of unbalance, just one devoid of chaos (though I do credit that you touch on this in the margin of your journal).  Though the races of Norrath would work together for the good of all, balance would still be maintained as all things age and die.  <br>
<br>
If I remember correctly, the initial problem at the creation was growth without decay.  With the introduction of death, balance was maintained and order restored.  This being the case, the only true thing that could truly disrupt the balance, and require Tunare to intervene, would be the ending of death, as this would clearly have world-ending effects, as anyone could clearly see.  A world that leaned toward love and goodness, True love, not the oppressive type often expounded by Paladins and Priests,  would not be a world unbalanced, as death remains.  And death is not evil, as it lifts us from this mortal coil to Tunare's gentle embrace.<br>
<br>
Now some may argue about the nature of Good/Evil, but that's a talk for another time.  But to compare the compassion of Good with the hate of Evil is not truly understand the definition and motivation of the two.<br>
<br>
/ooc If you want to wax philosophical, contact me in-game.  My character is firm in the belief of goodness and love being the only true ways, and is slowly pondering the relevance of the Gods when the only true being worthy of worship and following is the one who created even them.  Makes it a pain as she keeps trying to talk sense into the goblins and orcs she comes across...and they just don't seem very receptive to the Truth <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <br>
