</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ubjond.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Bjond</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/white_redspot.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 188<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(1/17/02 3:23:14 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1137.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> A Tier'dal ..</span><hr size=1> .. that truly embraces his heritage, hates even his creator, Innoruk.  Not all are that extreme, though.  I've had a number of dealings with them and there are wide variations.  Some, such as the well-known Lokar, are merely venal and just like gold and red wine.  Others are so full of hate even their own kind exile and hunt them -- witness the Teir'dal in Mistmoore.<br>
<br>
As for the Faer, they're just the other side of the same coin.  At the extreme, you have the do-gooder medling in everyone else's business on the assumption that she knows what's good and right for everyone (this is pretty much the same thing as the hate-mongering Tier that meddles for his own ends).  At the lesser extreme, there are the simple Faer that exist only to pursue knowledge.<br>
<br>
Basically, both races use their heritage to justify actions that they wish to indulge in and would perform regardless of race or religion.  They're all the same.  As the saying goes, &quot;Elves is elves&quot;. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/umoandor.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Moandor</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 38<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(1/17/02 6:19:00 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1137.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: A crisis of faith (long)</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> To others, while it is true that many individual Dark Elves follow discord, the entire structure of their society is based on the rule of law. In this sense they are much like the High elves. If you compare the two, you see the same great achievements in architecture, society, and the mastery of the intellectual and religious arts, these are hallmarks of an orderly society. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Laws are for the weak. <br>
<br>
Laws were created to protect those who cannot physically protect and defend themselves.  While it provides structure and strength to our race as a whole, it promotes weakness and submission to the hearts and minds of the individual. <br>
<br>
With the burden of these things called laws.... you bring weight upon the ambitions of our people, and you impose shackles and imprison their burning desires and the potential of their full talents. You suffocate the fate of those who are destined to become great among the Father's people.<br>
<br>
Your &quot;laws&quot; do nothing but cower the Teir'Dal to obey, they force us into mindless submission, they entice us to allow bureaucrats nobles and politicians to rule our lives! <br>
<br>
*snort* <br>
